# Angular Component Rules

This is a set of criteria to be able to consistently generate code for Angular components in a way that we all can follow the best practices.

The [Angular coding style](mdc:https:/angular.dev/style-guide) should be fully respected but never with regard to folder structure. On the other hand, rules written in this file should take precendence over the official Angular ones.

### Component path

Any Angular project in a repo or monorepo is split into app features or app domains. All those features should be located in the corresponding `src/app` of that Angular app project.

All Angular projects are referenced in [angular.json](mdc:angular.json).

The primary app feature of a modern project should be called "app" itself and it takes any symbol that can be re-used accross the app project. Take e.g. `src/app/app`. The "app/app", even if apparently redundant, is not an issue. It is actually ok because both folders have a different meaning. One is meant for source app code and the other one is the general app feature.

Criteria on folder structure will be explained in detail in a different rules file.

However, it is important to notice that components should be saved into 2 different directories:

- `src/app/feature-or-domain/containers`.
- `src/app/feature-or-domain/components`.

### Smart/Dumb component pattern

Components should follow the Smart/Dumb pattern to improve reusability, testing, and maintainability.

There are 2 types of components:

1. Smart (Container) Components:
   - Must be placed in 'containers' directories.
   - Should handle data fetching and state management.

2. Dumb (Presentational) Components:
   - Must be placed in 'components' directories.
   - Should only use inputs and outputs.

The folder structure would look like this:

```
src/app/
├── containers/
│   ├── user-list/
│   │   └── user-list.component.ts
│   └── user-details/
│       └── user-details.component.ts
└── components/
    ├── user-card/
    │   └── user-card.component.ts
    └── user-avatar/
        └── user-avatar.component.ts
```

Presentational components are subject of being migrated to library projects to be reused not only by 1 project but rather across them.

### Component file

It should always be suffixed with the corresponding Angular symbol e.g. in this case `.component.ts`.

It should always be accompanied by:

- Template file on HTML.
- Style file on SCSS.
- Unit testing file on TS named after the component file but adding ".spec" to the name.

All 4 files should have consistent naming between them. For example:

- `my-feature.component.ts`
- `my-feature.component.html`
- `my-feature.component.scss`
- `my-feature.component.spec.ts`

SCSS should be empty.

HMTL file should contain 1 div with a class that matches the component selector without the prefix. For example, if the component selector is "app-my-component", the template should look like this:

```html
<div class="my-component"></div>
```

`*.spec.ts` file should follow the Jest testing guidelines defined in the Jest rules.

The component file e.g. `my-feature.component.ts` should only contain the component class. We should not find variables, functions or data models in the file.

If any model should be declared, it should be written in a `*.model.ts` file for types and interfaces.

If any function should be declared, it should be written in a `*.util.ts` file for utility functions.

If any const variable should be declared, consider declaring it as a `static readonly` property in the component, but only if that information belongs solely to the component logic. If those values can be reused in other parts of the project, they probably belong to a `*.enum.ts` file.

TypeScript rules will be provided in a separate rules file.

### Component decorator

We should always use `OnPush` change detection strategy, except in the `AppComponent`.

Also `@Component` decorator metadata properties should be arranged alphabeticallly.

These properties are mandatory:

- changeDetection
- selector
- styleUrls
- templateUrl

A component selector should contain its prefix specified in the `angular.json` "prefix" property corresponding the project that the file belongs to.

Any new component should be standalone, so those components should also carry `standalone: true,`.

If a component is standalone, it should also contain the `imports` metadata and this should be an empty array. We should never import the `CommonModule`.

And also the "Component" suffix should be appended to the name of the class.

For example:

```ts
@Component({
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
  imports: [],
  selector: 'app-feature-component',
  standalone: true,
  styleUrls: ['./my-feature.component.scss'],
  templateUrl: './my-feature.component.html',
})
export class MyFeatureComponent {}
```

### Component constructor

Neither the constructor nor the `ngOnInit` lifecycle hook should be part of the boilerplate when generating a new component.

If we need to inject Angular services we should use Angular's [`inject` function](mdc:https:/angular.dev/reference/migrations/inject-function).

For any initialization logic, we should use the constructor instead of the OnInit lifecycle hook unless we are referencing any Angular input in it.

### Component members

Components are always declared as TypeScript classes.

Component members are specifically TypeScript class properties and methods.

When declaring TypeScript members we should totally avoid access modifiers, so no `public`, `protected` or `private`.

We will only use public and private members. All members are public by default. To declare the private ones we should use [EcmaScript private identifiers](mdc:https:/developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Classes/Private_properties) which prepend a hash (#) to the name of the member.

Any member that is not used in the template should be private.

All members should use the lowerCamelCase naming convention. No exception.

We should strictly respect the member ordering specified in the `.eslintrc.json` file located at the root of this repository. The name of the rule to follow is "@typescript-eslint/member-ordering" and only members specified there should be declared in the component class.

As a reference:

```json
// Member ordering (follow this order for class members)
"@typescript-eslint/member-ordering": [
  "warn",
  {
    "default": {
      "memberTypes": [
        "public-static-field",
        "#private-field",
        "public-get",
        "public-set",
        "public-field",
        "constructor",
        "public-method",
        "#private-method"
      ],
      "order": "alphabetically"
    }
  }
]
```

`@Input()` properties should be considered as normal public properties and therefore they should respect the same member ordering.

All members should be strongly typed. Methods should always declare a return type. If the method does not return anything we should specify `void`.

`any` will never considered as a type. If we need to type a value which type we do not know yet, we will use `unknown` instead.

We should create as many properties as possible as [Angular signals](mdc:https:/angular.dev/guide/signals).

Of course we should not type injections or observables as signals.

Observable properties should use Finish notation, so their name should end with a dollar ($) suffix. This applies the same for `Subject` observables.

If a method is used to return a value in a template and does not take any parameter we should make it into a
getter.

### Component property initialization

All component properties should be initialized to a value except required inputs.

Init criteria as follows:

- Strings to emtpy string `''`.
- Arrays to empty array `[]`.
- Booleans to either `true` or `false`, on convenience.
- Objects to `null` or to the corresponding init object.

### Component max lines

Any component file should not contain more than 300 lines. If more lines are needed the component should be split into several presentational components.

Any component method should not contain more than 20 lines. If more lines are needed the method should be split into different private methods.

### Observables

We should avoid as much as possible subscribing to observables in the component class. We should always try to subscribe in the template by using [Angular's AsyncPipe](mdc:https:/angular.dev/api/common/AsyncPipe).

However, if we do need to subscribe to an observable in the TypeScript class, we should always use [Angular's takeUntilDestroyed](mdc:https:/angular.dev/api/core/rxjs-interop/takeUntilDestroyed), to avoid memory leaks.

For this, we need to declare a little boilerplate, a property called `#destroyRef` assigned to [Angular's DestroyRef](mdc:https:/angular.dev/api/core/DestroyRef). For example:

```ts
export class MyComponent {
  #destroyRef = inject(DestroyRef);
  [...]

  mySubscriptionMethod(): void {
    this.#myObservable$
      .pipe(
        map((element: unknown) => element.prop),
        takeUntilDestroyed(this.#destroyRef)
      )
      .subscribe((elementProp: unknown) => {
        console.log(elementProp);
      });
  }
```

If we use the observable property, either in the HTML template or in the TS class, and we are going to subscribe to it from 2 or more different places, we will need to set it as multicast by adding this piping operator:

```ts
shareReplay({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true }),
```

One more important thing: `takeUntilDestroyed` shouls always come last in the [RxJS](mdc:https:/rxjs.dev) piping sequence it should belong to the outtest nesting level, so to the primary observable, the first one declared if there is any observable chaining or composition.

### Signals

Angular signals are in developer preview in version 16, but we can use them as long as we do not use the `mutate()` method with them, since that method is deprecated in further versions.

Signals should be typed strong as well:

```ts
signalReadOnly: Signal<number> = computed<number>(() => this.signalWritable() * 2);
signalWritable: WritableSignal<number> = signal<number>(0);
```

In general, we will prefer to use signals to observables, if possible.

### Example

```ts
@Component({
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
  imports: [],
  selector: 'fzo-my',
  standalone: true,
  styleUrl: './my.component.scss',
  templateUrl: './my.component.html',
})
export class MyComponent {
  static readonly staticProp = 'staticProp';
  #privateProp = 'privateProp';
  #router = inject(Router);
  get privatePropGetter(): string {
    return this.#privateProp;
  }
  set privatePropSetter(value: string) {
    this.privatePropGetter = value;
  }
  publicProp$: Observable<Scroll> = this.#router.events.pipe(
    shareReplay({ bufferSize: 1, refCount: true }),
    filter((event): event is Scroll => event instanceof Scroll),
    take(1),
  );
  signalReadOnly: Signal<number> = computed<number>(() => this.signalWritable() * 2);
  signalWritable: WritableSignal<number> = signal<number>(0);

  constructor() {
    /**
     * We still need `takeUntilDestroyed` despite of the fact
     * that we are taking care of the memory leaks already
     * by using `take(1)` because user can suddenly navigate
     * to another route before the unsubscription happens.
     */
    this.publicProp$
      .pipe(
        filter((event: Scroll) => [1].includes(event.routerEvent.id)),
        tap(() => {
          // Do something on first navigation.
        }),
        takeUntilDestroyed(this.#destroyRef),
      )
      .subscribe();
    // This is similar to an RxJS subscription.
    effect(() => {
      // We tell signal's dependency graph to track that signal.
      this.signalWritable();
      untracked(() => {
        console.log('Here I can use the current value of some other signal.');
      });
    });
  }

  publicMethod(): void {
    this.#privateMethod();
  }

  #privateMethod(): string {
    return MyComponent.staticProp;
  }
}
```

A separate rules file for signals will be provided.
